❌ Bronin has decided that the provisions of Hartford’s Living Wage Ordinance magically do not apply to the workers at Dunkin Donuts Park. That’s ridiculous.

I respect Paul, have a good relationship with Paul and have been on his show many times. (And I hope to do so in the future.) He brings much needed discourse to our political process.That said, Republicans like to accuse "the liberal media" of bias so isn't it only fair that when that bias shows up in "conservative media" they be called out, too? (And you wonder why the approval rating of the media is as low as Congress.) You get to see it in his own words and from his lips, not some edited 40 character tweet from 3 yrs ago summarized by a radio host. Ronald Reagan's 80/20 rule (voting w/ me 80% of the time as opposed to 100% means you're my friend not my enemy) is well known.  Reasonable people, ie, Mississippi voters, know that you don't see eye-to-eye on everything, even though the media establishment would have you believe otherwise. An Attorney General is required to apply the Constitution and the laws and must use independent judgement in carrying out the job.  Andy Taggart owns that fact.  Any lawyer worth his or her salt will tell you that fact. Why? Because the law, and life, are not black and white (or red and blue); step into a courtroom in our judicial system (set up by our Founders) and you will see this fact. And make no mistake, the AG must have those courtroom skills to represent you, me and every other Mississippian. I have faith, as I am sure Andy Taggart does, that the voters know when they are being played and when they aren't. So, take a look. Make up your own mind.

ad_creative_body: Katherine G. Johnson is an American mathematician whose calculations of orbital mechanics as a NASA employee were critical to the success of the first and subsequent U.S. crewed spaceflights. During her 35-year career at NASA and its predecessor, the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, she earned a reputation for mastering complex manual calculations and helped pioneer the use of computers to perform the tasks. The space agency noted her "historical role as one of the first African-American women to work as a NASA scientist". This year NASA renamed the Independent Verification and Validation Facility (IV&V) in West Virginia the Katherine Johnson IV&V Facility, according to the association. #wcw #womenleaders #womeninhistory #hiddenfigures #spaceexploration #scientist 📸: David Bowman

This morning, I had the privilege of introducing the members of the Scituate Summer Fun Foundation during Senate Session. The foundation was started by four freshmen students at Scituate High School to help raise awareness and resources for families experiencing homelessness on the South Shore.
 
The idea started after these students were asked to focus on a particular issue in town as part of their Community Service Learning class at Scituate High. The students visited a local family shelter, Carolina Hill, and met with the program director, staff, and the families who live there to learn about what they may need for support as they strive to rebuild their lives and become more independent.
 
The Summer Fun Foundation was started and they helped raise $600 to help families in need at the Carolina Hill Shelter. In July, these students went back to visit the shelter to bring the families gift cards, toys, beach towels and sunscreen. I would like to thank Patrick Sullivan, Kiera Reidy, Carly Bolton, and Leiney Smith for truly making a difference in the lives of these families. I could not be more proud of the work these students have done.

Seeking UNDERWRITERS for MAUI CAUSES' 6th Year of WEEKLY TV SHOWS Airing On Akaku Channel 55. 

Any donation is appreciated, however, three sponsorship mentions per show for $1000 during each of our broadcasts that air multiple times each week, are a great opportunity for your company to get positive exposure in our community and to support the Not-For-Profits, Environmental and Progressive Causes our shows bring attention to. We intend to product 12 shows before the end of this year with sponsorship available for $1000 per show. 

As a multi-media production team MAUI CAUSES cost effectively produces and distributes relevant content on many of the complex issues facing Maui today. 

Our island is locked in a hundreds year old stranglehold by plantation powers that never did and still don't serve the greater good. Only the people, standing up for what is right, on issue after issue, against the "Powers That Be" can bring the kind of change that Maui needs and deserves.

Maui Causes Episode #93 is a perfect example. The current call for community input to find a solution to the lingering debacle of the Maui Lani lots along Palama Drive is a perfect opportunity to shine a light on the continuing lack of accountability within Maui County Government. 

We believe that Maui's Corporation Counsel Patrick Wong acted illegally is 2011 to hide from the Maui County Council an alternative settlement proposal that was accepted by the Developer to turn the property into affordable housing.

By withholding the alternative proposal, Wong was able to engineer an $11 Million deal brokered through his law school pal. In return, it is believed that Wong received over $1 Million which he claims were gambling winnings but for which he cannot provide tax records to verify.

Wong resigned as Corporation Counsel in disgrace yet his replacement, Moana Luety, continues to pervert the system acting as an independent branch of government that is accountable to no one. 

These are the kind of issues we are bold enough to address on our shows. maui Causes is dedicated to being a positive disruption to the Status Quo, which is desperately needed if Maui is to mature as a modern municipality with appropriate accountability and transparency that has been missing here for so long.

Taxpayer-owned Mayo Regional Hospital stands to lose at least 100 jobs if the agreement with Northern Light Health is executed.

The commitment to comply with the WARN Act (a federal law which requires advance notice when at least 100 jobs are eliminated) isn't in the agreement without cause. 

Northern Light Health doesn't need any of the support staff that Mayo employs. They already have staff in Bangor/Portland to do that. 

On top of that, we know that Northern Light Health is eliminating medical services at rural hospitals to improve profitability so they can borrow more money to build a new hospital in Portland.

The loss of any jobs at Mayo as a result of of the integration will prove to be a major loss of solid jobs that provide economic stability to the region. 

Even if Mayo had to cut jobs to remain independent, the result surely wouldn't be as devastating to the region as what the current agreement will accomplish.

Dear Family and Friends,

I’m honored and privileged to be a California Delegate for District 42nd and blessed to have been elected Vice Chair of Region 9 covering Riverside County and Imperial County for the Chicano Latino Caucus.  
In Riverside County, 1.4 million voters are eligible to register. As of Jan. 2, 958,000 county residents have registered. 
Of the total Riverside County registered voters, 38 percent, or 364,600 voters, have registered as Democrats. The Republican Party has 335,600 (35 Percent) registered voters. We can Make a Change! Or We must Make a Change! We MUST turn Blue!!
As you can see, we have an urgent matter to register to vote and turn our counties BLUE. All energized leaders, mothers, fathers, students are eligible to vote and the community is ESSENTIAL. we plan to relentlessly campaign within our counties in order to hit our mark and we will keep you informed of future events.
It’s unconscionable what Trump has, and continues to do to our Country with the separation of children from their parents. People leaving in fear, massive killing throughout the United States with no accountability, and no solution. I ask you, what in America are we making great again?

(Although my business and all the children’s charities I support occupy my calendar, I am committed to make a change but I cannot do it alone.)
We need your help to get Trump out of office!

In the wise words of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. “If you fail to act now, history will have to record that the greatest tragedy of this period of social transition was not the strident clamor of the bad people, but the appalling silence of the good people.”

Voting is a privilege and silence is Consent. The only way the priorities and concerns of our communities will rise to the top of the nation’s agenda is if our voices are heard. Click here to register: https://registertovote.ca.gov/
We have the freedoms to make change, It’s time to use them!
I will be hosting a lunch with Nancy Pelosi (Speaker of the House), and you can bet that I will make her aware of our county and request her assistance to give us guidance and wisdom on how we can play our part for the successful outcome we all hope and deserve.

These are some of many of my charities I am committed to.
• Sandy’s House DTLA (for runaway Girls in Skidrow)
• Hollenbeck Youth Center East Los Angeles
• Boys and Girls Club Temecula, Murrieta and Lake Elsinore
•  Adopted Children 
• The Lupus Foundation 
• St. Jude Children’s Hospital 
• Children Hospital of Los Angeles 

Progressive, Moderate, Independent, Republican, Democrat, we are all in this together. I cannot do this without you!

Vote Blue No Matter Who!
Love Sandy Piña

The Department of Education (ED) sent colleges and universities across the country three edicts (in 2001, 2011, and 2014) requiring them to create campus disciplinary systems that lacked basic elements of due process and failed to ensure fundamental fairness. If colleges refused to cooperate with this “rule by letter,” ED threatened to withhold their federal funding. 

NCLA’s client, Dr. Mukund Vengalattore, was an assistant physics professor at Cornell on track for tenure when in 2014 a graduate student falsely accused him of sexual misconduct. At the Department of ED's insistence, Cornell tore down basic protections in its own disciplinary proceedings by adopting a “mere preponderance of the evidence” standard, instead of a "clear and convincing" standard for assessing guilt. Dr. Vengalattore was subjected to a biased, discriminatory and fundamentally unfair system that was structured, by the Department, to ensure he would be disciplined.

Independent Women's Forum is hosting a Facebook Live event where NCLA attorney Caleb Krukenberg will discuss Dr. Vengalattore's case and how NCLA is challenging the Dept. of ED's enforcement of Title IX.

Atria Kennebunk is now looking for Full-time and Part-time Dining Room Servers!

Job Responsibilities:
* Responsible for setting and clearing tables, taking residents food and beverage orders and serving residents in a timely professional manner.
* Provide a high level of customer service and promote a restaurant style dining atmosphere.
* Work closely with the culinary service director and/or executive director to keep residents satisfied with food and dining programs.
* Review daily menu with residents.
* Takes and delivers accurate meal orders to residents and guests.
* Assist with preparation and execution of special events, banquets, and theme meals.
* When applicable acquaint new residents with menus, seating, and dining options and hours.
* Communicate resident likes and dislikes to Director of Culinary Services and/or Restaurant Manager for menu planning purposes and resident satisfaction.

Required Skills and Qualifications:
* Strong communication and teamwork skills.
* Strong organization and time management skills. 

Benefits of working at Atria include:
* Tuition Reimbursement
* Health insurance
* Training and growth opportunities
* Paid time off, including holidays
* Complimentary meals
* 401(k) retirement plan
* And more!

What’s the difference between a job and a meaningful, rewarding career? The people you serve. When you work at Atria, you have a front-row seat to the amazing life stories of the wisest people on earth. What’s more, you are part of an extraordinary company – one that’s investing in the future of senior living by investing in you. 

Atria Senior Living is a leading operator of independent living, assisted living, supportive living, and memory care communities in more than 200 locations in 27 states and seven Canadian provinces. We create vibrant communities where older adults can thrive and participate, know that their contributions are valued, and enjoy access to opportunities and support that help them continue making a difference in our world.

Atria is an equal opportunity employer committed to providing equal employment opportunities without regard to race, color, religion, sex (including pregnancy), sexual orientation, age, national origin, disability, genetic information, veteran status, or any other classification protected by applicable law. Atria will not tolerate harassment or discrimination based on any of these protected classifications.

“As your Receiver of Taxes, I will continue to be a public advocate for Long Island’s Working Families. Brookhaven Town has a tremendous ability to look out for our quality of life and the Middle Class. As a City Attorney and Teamster with Local 237, I saw first hand how unions protected public workers and I saw how Administrations unfairly treated workers to balance budgets. As taxpayers we have rights to demand equal treatment and equal town services (ie roads, drainage, lighting, beautification, parks) and I will personally monitor that our communities are properly allocated resources fairly and not just to select communities.

I will put taxpayers first so all residents are treated fairly and so they feel they are getting a just return of services on the taxes they pay. I ask for your support and vote this November 5th so we can Build a Better Brookhaven Together.” - Dom Pascual

YUBA COUNTY RESIDENTS WEIGH IN ABOUT INDEPENDENT BOARDS

Topline: An overwhelming number of Yuba County residents believe the Board of Supervisors should not sit on the Board of the Yuba Water Agency (YWA). Less than 20% of residents believe the combined boards are good for the County. 

Candidates running in the March 2020 primary should take note - Running on a campaign promise of separating the two boards could be a winning ticket. If elected officials aren’t willing to make changes, County residents should consider a referendum movement.

Findings: Yuba Vision conducted an online survey that asked Yuba County residents several questions about the YWA board make-up. 140 people took the survey and they were screened to confirm they were Yuba County residents. Questions offered multiple choice responses, as well as write-in commentary.

Even though a vast majority of respondents do not believe it’s a good thing to have combined boards, more than 66% did not know that when they vote for a Supervisor they are also voting for a Board Director on the YWA. (Note: Should the County Elections Department do a better job of communicating the dual role in the voter materials?)

Nearly 90% of those who do not believe it’s a good thing to have combined boards cited, “a conflict of interest” as their primary point of concern. Nearly 70% of these same people indicated that the, “lack of independent oversight,” and over 60% selected, “Supervisors are not focusing 100% on County issues,” as reasons for concern. Nearly 60% selected, “Agency money is sometimes used for political reasons.”

For those who believe that having combined Boards is good for Yuba County, nearly 60% selected, “We have better representation,” and “It reduces bureaucracy,” as their primary reasons of support. Nearly 30% believe, “It’s a better use of a Supervisor’s time.”

One of the more interesting findings was that when respondents were told that half of a Supervisor’s salary is paid by YWA (which presumably would mean that half of a Supervisor’s time is spent working for YWA), nearly 30% of respondents who favor a combined board, flip to no longer supporting a combined YWA Board. 

Some of the more interesting commentary:
From a respondent who does not support combined boards - “The question arises, is a candidate running to be a Supervisor or more to be on the YWA Board.” 

From a respondent who supports combined boards - “Anything that reduces the amount of people between a goal and its inception is good. More government means less actual work and more indecisive dithering.” 

From a respondent who flipped away from supporting a combined board: 
“It appears their decisions could possibly be misinterpreted in many different ways based upon who is paying their annual salary.”

The survey ran for a week. While the total sample size is relatively small for quantitative findings, given that the opinion range is quite wide, it does reflect a convincing trend that would more than likely be represented in a larger sample size.

The axe of political retribution has begun to swing.

To be an Independent candidate for mayor, I had to obtain at least 288 signatures from voters in Terre Haute who support my right to be on the ballot. The signing of this petition did not indicate an individual’s support of my candidacy, only that the person agreed with my right to be a candidate. 

Citizens from all along the political spectrum signed my petition. Among them were people involved with the Democratic party, the Republican party, Independents, Libertarians, and everything in between. 

Earlier this week, several people from the Democratic party received the letter pictured below.
  
To those of you facing this persecution from your party:  I appreciate your courage to sign my petition. I realize some of you may not even intend to vote for me, and that’s ok. Thank you for standing up for my right as a U.S. citizen to run for office without having to join a political party.

To my supporters:  Thank you for supporting me--of your own free will. I’m grateful that so many of you are behind me, not because a political party is requiring you to be, but because you believe supporting me is the best way to move our community forward.

This act of political retribution is a prime example of why I’m running as an Independent. “Politics as usual” in Terre Haute needs to cease. We can do better.

Hate crimes based on political ideology. 

The FBI has defined a hate crime as a “criminal offense against a person or property motivated in whole or in part by an offender’s bias against a race, religion, disability, sexual orientation, ethnicity or gender.”

A political ideology is a certain set of principles or doctrines in a social movement composed of a large group of people that explains how society should work, and offers a political and cultural blueprint for a certain social order.

The shootings in El Paso and Dayton have prompted discussions on mass killings, mass shootings, and hate crime. 

The FBI defines a mass killing as any instance in which four or more people are killed, not counting the suspected killer. So if you follow that definition, there have been about 30 shootings in 2019 that qualify as mass killings.

The Gun Violence Archive, an independent organization tracking gun violence, defines a mass shooting as a situation in which four or more people are shot. By this metric there have been about 250 mass shootings in 2019. 

We have looked at data over the last 10 years involving mass shootings and have found 18 instances that qualify as hate crimes based on political ideology. We included 2 standout incidents of hate crimes using weapons other than firearms. Below are these 20 incidents, with a brief summary to start. Please share any other incidents of hate crimes based on political ideology that we may have overlooked. The question is, should we as a society try to reduce hate crimes based on political ideology? And if so, how? Share your views at synthisophy.com!

White Supremacist: 4

Investigators discovered evidence that the shooter had been exploring violent ideologies" and had created a list of potential targets, including the Garlic Festival as well as "religious organizations, courthouses, federal buildings and political institutions involving both the Republican and Democratic parties. Searches found he owned both left-wing and right-wing literature.

The Poway synagogue shooting involved a gunman armed with an AR-15 style rifle that fired shots inside the Chabad of Poway synagogue in Poway, California, a city approximately 20 miles north of San Diego. The attack took place on the last day of the Jewish Passover holiday, which fell on a Shabbat.[5]

A man opened fire in the Tree of Life synagogue in an antisemitic attack, killing eleven people and injuring six others (including four police officers).  Using the online social network Gab, the shooter had earlier posted anti-Semitic comments against HIAS (formerly, Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society) in which Tree of Life was a supporting participant. Referring to Central American migrant caravans and immigrants, he posted on Gab shortly before the attack that "HIAS likes to bring invaders in that kill our people. I can't sit by and watch my people get slaughtered. Screw your optics, I'm going in.”

The driver of the car had driven from Ohio to attend the rally. He previously espoused neo-Nazi and white supremacist beliefs.

Alexandria, Virginia, 6.14.17: 4 injured
2017 Congressional baseball shooting: A gunman shot and wounded four people, including Republican Congressman and House Majority Whip Steve Scalise, while they were practicing for the Congressional Baseball Game. The shooter was a left-wing activist while Scalise was a Republican member of Congress. The Virginia Attorney General concluded the shooter's attack was "an act of terrorism...fueled by rage against Republican legislators".

Fresno, California, 4.18.17: 4 killed
A man killed a security guard at a hotel, then killed three other people five days later. The attacks, committed against white people by a black suspect, are believed to have been racially motivated and the suspect believed there was a race war taking place between white and black people. Orlando, Florida, 6.12.16: 49 killed, 53 injured
Orlando nightclub shooting: A gunman killed 49 people and wounded 53 others in a shooting at Pulse, a gay nightclub. In a 9-1-1 call made shortly after the shooting began, the gunman swore allegiance to the leader of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant, Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, and said the U.S. killing of Abu Waheeb in Iraq the previous month "triggered" the shooting.

San Bernardino, California, 12.2.15: 14 dead, 22 injured
A married couple opened fire on the husband's colleagues at a work training event. According to the FBI's investigation, the perpetrators were "homegrown violent extremists" inspired by foreign terrorist groups. They were not directed by such groups and were not part of any terrorist cell or network. FBI investigators have said that they had become radicalized over several years prior to the attack, consuming "poison on the internet" and expressing a commitment to jihadism and martyrdom in private messages to each other.

Colorado Springs, Colorado, 11.19.15: 3 dead, 9 injured
A man killed two civilians and a police officer and wounded nine others inside a Planned Parenthood clinic before surrendering to police. The shootings are thought to have been motivated by the suspect's anti-abortion views.

Minneapolis, Minnesota, 11.23.15: 5 injured
During a Black Lives Matter protest related to the shooting of Jamar Clark, a man opened fire and injured five protestors. Prosecutors accused the men of being white supremacists and trying to disrupt the protest.

Chattanooga, Tennessee, 7.16.15: 5 dead, 1 wounded
A man committed a drive-by shooting at a military recruitment center in a strip mall, wounding one Marine. With police in pursuit, he drove to a U.S. Navy Reserve center and rammed his vehicle through a gate. He fatally wounded a Navy sailor, killed four Marines, and wounded a police officer before being killed by police. The FBI later determined the gunman had been motivated by propaganda published by terrorist organizations.

Charleston, South Carolina, 6.17.15: 9 dead, 1 wounded
A white supremacist killed nine black people during a prayer service at the Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church, wounding one other. He was taken into custody by police, and later said that he committed the shootings in an attempt to start a "race war".  The shooting targeted one of the United States' oldest black churches, which has long been a site for community organization around civil rights. 

Chapel Hill, North Carolina, 2.10.15: 3 killed
The shooter gunned down his three Muslim neighbors inside their condominium. He was an outspoken atheist and gun enthusiast who had expressed hatred of Islam and had a history of confronting neighbors of color with a firearm in his hand.

Overland Park, Kansas, 4.13.14: 3 killed
A white supremacist went to the Jewish Community Center of Greater Kansas City and Village Shalom and killed three, two near the community center and one at the retirement community. He was a Klansman, neo-Nazi and former political candidate.

Oak Creek, Wisconsin, 8.5.12: 7 killed, 4 injured
The perpetrator, a member of the Hammerskins and various white power and neo-Nazi bands, fatally shot six people at a Sikh temple before being killed by responding police officers.

Tucson, Arizona, 1.8.11: 6 killed, 15 injured
A man killed six people and injured fifteen during an assassination attempt of democratic U.S. Representative Gabrielle Giffords before he was tackled and arrested. Giffords was wounded in the attack but survived.  Conspiracy theories had a profound effect on him. Reports appearing after the shooting noted similarities between the statements made by the shooter and those publicized by the far-right conspiracy theorist David Wynn Miller

Fort Hood, Texas, 11.5.2009: 13 dead, 33 injured
Fort Hood Military Base shooting: A U.S. army psychiatrist opened fire and killed thirteen individuals and injured 33 others. Days after the shooting, reports in the media revealed that a Joint Terrorism Task Force had been aware of a series of e-mails between Hasan and the Yemen-based Imam Anwar al-Awlaki, who had been monitored by the NSA as a security threat, and that Hasan's colleagues had been aware of his increasing radicalization for several years.
